  <div class="bgimg-2 w3-display-container">
  <div class="w3-display-middle">
    <span class="w3-xxlarge w3-text-black w3-wide">Little Angels Ceremony</span>
  </div>
  </div>
<!-- Container (Portfolio Section) -->
<div class="w3-content w3-container w3-padding-64">

  <p> <i> <center> By: Brianna Lewis </center> </i>
  <br>
  The Procession of Little Angels will be taking over Armory Park this Saturday as will many other events involved with the All Souls Procession throughout Tucson.
<br> <br>
It is a family friendly event that teaches children to acknowledge and honor their loved ones that have passed away. Throughout the day, there are series of events and activities that will take place. This includes, arts and crafts and live performances.
<br> <br>
One of the most common activities is the decorating of cardboard wings. Throughout the day children will go to the station and put their artistic abilities to work. They will often times paint them, write a message, and even paste their loved one’s photographs on it.
<br> <br>
“The event is something that encourages rogue, and integration, creativity, imagination, and strengthens community” said Jhon Sanders, the director for Little Angels. “The wings epitomize those things in some ways.”
<br> <br>
Although the children do not realize any of those qualities are being radiated by their wings, the way they can easily express their imagination and thoughts through art truly sends a message.
<br> <br>
Minor details from Halloween are contributed to Little Angels. Except, they added in the forgotten traditions of this haunted celebration.
<br> <br>
<center><img src="http://i67.tinypic.com/2qis57s.jpg"style="height:350px;width=600px;"></center>
<br> <br>
“We’ve taken back what Halloween used to be and what it was originally; it used to be harvest festival, and an ancestor’s festival where the world of the living and world of the dead are at their highest point of overlap,” said Sanders.
<br> <br>
According to Sanders, incorporating some of the most important attributes of Halloween is a fun way to create an opportunity for children to learn more about the importance of their ancestors and others who have passed.
<br> <br>
Alters of loved ones who have passed away are also big attributions to Little Angels. The interaction with families who have suffered loss is an eye opening experience for children. For most of them, it is startling to realize that kids can die too, but it is an experience for them to learn about life and also death.
<br> <br>
“It is good for the kids and it’s good for Maria and her family,” said Sanders.
<br> <br>
Maria is a woman who displays an alter every year in order to honor the loss of her daughter. Jhon explained that the alters create a great opportunity for dialogue and opportunity for the children. Therefore, the meaning of life and death can be better understood. Throwing the children all together for an entire day is also a way to create community. Families with all kinds of different backgrounds come together to celebrate their loved ones.
<br> <br>
There are a series of mini performances that are held throughout the day, but when night fall arrives the main event kicks in. As a unique attribution to the performance, most of the showcase inspiration comes from children.
<br> <br>
Sharon O’Brien the artistic director of Little Angels also helps run an organization called, "Stories That Soar." The organization goes around to schools with a “magic and hungry box” thats lets students tell stories. The children are able to write whatever they feel. Then other actors and children reenact some of the stories that the kids wrote.
<br> <br>
<center><img src="http://i65.tinypic.com/2rr78z5.jpg"style="height:350px;width=600px;"></center>
<br> <br>
“Kids love to write for the magic box because they get to be free and write about whatever they want with no restrictions,” said O’Brien.
<br> <br>
Often times, children write about death, loss, and sadness. Which fits perfect with the theme of Little Angels and the message it sends. Over time, stories that would be fitting, are performed for the finale at Little Angels. It is easy for them to incorporate the stories because the whole point of Little Angels is to view the All Souls Procession from a child’s point of view.
<br> <br>
“These stories, which are written by children explore the themes of loss, death, life, and really the celebration of life,” said O’Brien.
<br> <br>
The stories that are showcased are performed by students from the Tucson Circus Arts. O’Brien and her team make it an effort to make every contribution of Little Angels involved with children. Therefore, the stories that are acted out are usually done by young actors and actresses.
<br> <br>
With events that’s are specifically based for children, it is easy for them to stay engaged while learning about All Souls. A full day of events will leave children with a whole new view on the Procession.
<br> <br>
For those who are looking to get involved, throughout the planning process of Little Angels, there are a series of workshops that anyone can attend. Visitors of Little Angels are also able to bring photos and remembrances of their fallen children and place the items upon the alter. Although the event is mainly aimed towards children, the event has ways for all age groups to interact.</p>
